From {{etyl|NL.|en}}  ''anergia'', from Greek ''[[an-#Etymology_3|an-]]'' + ''ergon'' ("work").
# {{context|physics|lang=en}} Dilute or disorganized [[energy]], which cannot be transformed into work.
#:''The maximum fraction of an energy form which (in a reversible process) can be transformed into work is called exergy. The remaining part is called anergy, and this corresponds to the waste heat.''<ref>Honerkamp, J. ♦ Statistical Physics ♦ Springer, 2002, p. 298</ref>
#:''To be useful, internal energy has to be concentrated. The more dilute or disorganized the internal energy, the less useful it is ...''<ref>Newman, Jay ♦ Physics of the Life Sciences ♦ Springer, 2008, p. 336</ref>
# {{context|medicine|lang=en}} A lack of [[response]] to an [[antigen]] or [[antibody]].
